\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 How did you spend your free time then, did you have hobbies or collect anything or did you go fishing or walks or bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Well we used to go walks like a bit of hiking and all that of a Sunday when you got a bit older and like that and - and do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Did you go to theatres or concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Yes. Oh yes. Go to all the pictures and theatres.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 This is while you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Yes, if the - if we had the money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 You told me your parents gave you a penny a week didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Oh aye, yes. That's all you got for a penny Sunday. Sat'day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Did you get any help from people outside the house to help with the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Relations or friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 They all had a lot of their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Suppose she was ill and confined to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 A neighbour'd come in. A neighbour. There was - you always had good neighbours in them days, one helped the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 This is when your youngest sisters were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Yes. Like that and she used to keep me off school to do, you know, to do this and the other and look 
after the food and all that when I was only about ten or eleven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Did you have relatives living nearby apart from Auntie Mary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Oh yes, plenty. Yes, me mother had about four brothers there in the - that lived in the Adelphi but they all had famili
es of their own. I used to go there and play with the kids and me cousins and all like that, go over }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14765897\charrsid7603217 Broughton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
 there was some lived there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Did your parents have a lot of friends and did they share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Well - they really didn't - I 
can't remember, only when the relations come like, owt like that they'd - perhaps send out for a drink or make a sandwich and - that's all I can remember about when I was little, I don't remember 'em going like we go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Did they come for special occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Yes, special -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Or did they come when they wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 No, no, special occasions, like -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 What about neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 No, she never neighboured. No. She'd have a talk at the door and that, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 When you had people that came did they make their own }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14765897\charrsid7603217 amusements}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 ?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
Oh well they did, they used to sing and do, yes, they'd - they'd sing and - have a laugh you know or - talking about old times more than anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 In the days before 1918 people used to divide people up into g
roups and classes, can you tell me what the different classes and groups were, do you remember from when you - were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Well you knew then that - you know - that would seem to be pretty well off, had a regular job and - probably a foreman at the C
opper or - something on the railway or something like that. Well they seem - and especially if they have a sideboard and all this - oh yes, as soon as they got a sideboard and shades on it - vases and shades - oh you was well off then. They was really wel
l off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Did you think of some people belonging to one class and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
Well I used to think they was a bit better off of course because they'd have perhaps a tea service or cups and saucers where we only had - cups with no handle or some
thing like - mugs in fact there was that many of us and no pots half of the time we drank out of little basins and - one thing and another, yes. You know, they'd no money to buy all this stuff you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Can you tell me what class you though you belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
Well I always thought we was poor, very poor with having - having me father's wages coming in and then 'til our Mag started work and then - and then she was - hers was four shilling a week - but it was a little bit because the tent was only fou
r and threepence a week then and - that was the rent, if you got one working like and then - but anybody that lived in the shops like Perkins at the corner used - 'cos he was dressed well and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 You felt shopkeepers were a different class did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
Oh yes, they was always well off and that and - the O'Gars that had a greengrocers in Adelphi in Silk Street at the time I used to wear their old clothes and - same with the corner pub, the girls - they used to give me their - girl was my size and I used
 to have her last years reefer coat and - one thing and another and - me mother used to go on - there was women went round in them days that used to go with plants to these posh houses. Plants - and exchange them, what they called plant hawkers and they u
s
ed to exchange them for old clothes, old shoes, old shoes, old coats and things like that. Well then they'd come and sell the secondhand things so I had another girl that lived at Sale or somewhere, I don't know, but I used to think, I hope she gets a new
 coat this year because she was my size and I was always well off and then they - what I'd done with they was handed down to the younger ones you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14765897\charrsid7603217 
So - we - Mrs Brow her name was, she was a plant hawker, I remember it quite well, her coming, has Mrs Brow been and me mother'd wash and iron 'em and - they'd be on the line before you come home from school.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 You hoped she'd go to this place where this girl was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Yes. Girl was. Every now and again they used to go round to the same houses and take pl
ants, fern plants and different things and the people that was better off outside like Manchester way, Sale or Prestwich or out like that, they had their regular run you see these women with the big baskets on their arm, shawl on, and they used to exchang
e
 for old clothes, shoes or anything. Yes, oh yes, and then they used to sell them on to the what they call the Flat Iron in them days. By Trinity church, yes, Trinity church, you could go on there and you could get a beautiful voile blouse for a - a shill
i
ng or any - a shilling or copper, you know, you could get rigged out nearly for a shilling if you had nowt, and then at the top of Cannon Street in Adelphi there was Williams's and - every Thursday morning they used to buy pledged articles out of - that h
a
d run out of pawn shops, you know, that - that people had pawned and left in, bundles of washing. So she had a big skip basket with a lid on and we used to go up there every Thursday, mam can I get - how much have you got? She'd say, here's tuppence, go a
n
d see what you can get. And - many a time Lizzie Anne her name was, Lizzie Anne Williams, Lizzie Anne used to say, go on, you've got that, you've only got tuppence, I want - I should have had another penny for that. And you used to come with knickers and 
all sorts you know. All out of this basket top of Cannon - and somebody put it in the Reporter, oh a couple of years ago, about Lizzie }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14765897\charrsid7603217 Anne\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217  - this Williams's and I thought - I've never wrote a letter in me life to the papers, never, and I felt more like w
riting to say about the many a good - bargain I'd had for pennies and tuppence and if she had - you'd put it in your pocket many a time, pair of knickers or something like that and she'd say, have you got out else but we wouldn't let on we'd got this in y
our pocket. Like handkerchief you know, as big as handkerchief.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Were you taught to treat some people differently from others, were you ever told to show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Oh yes - oh - be nice to them you know, to anybody, we was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Were three people you were taught to show respect to especially do you remember, anyone you called sir or master?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
Oh well, the priest, always the priest, always - and they always used to come round visiting in them days, you know, the - oh yes, and the - t
he nuns or anything like that you know regarding we was - it was knocked into us like, religion - religion, it don't do you no harm I don't think to be - well I mean, not to me it hasn't. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 It's been a comfort to you from what you've said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Wel
l, and I've lost me children like that as I've said and it - a lot have turned from the church, I know two or three that's - 'cos they've lost their husband has turned away from the church and that's silly because - it must take them for a purpose, some w
ay.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Who did you consider were the most important people in the district you lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
Well - as I've told you, the publicans, you know, they had the pub at the corner and - the shopkeepers and you'd go out of your road to do anything if they wan
ted an errand for them because you thought they was - they was it and especially up the brew, we used to call it up the brew then from Adelphi, was all brews you see. Up the brew, different ones, ooh, they're well off and then all this and the other 'cos 
they had money coming in probably - their dads had good jobs so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 And they would have a better class home you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15294545 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Who do you think the priests mixed with when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5270951 MB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 Ooh, they used to come round visiting a lot
 but they never do now. They do that - they did that. Every - every - oh you didn't know when they was coming, they used to just walk in because I remember once this man, be dead and gone now, but I'd gone in for this girl, I was about twelve or thirteen 
and we had a Father Foy that was belonged Salford, you know, bred and born in Salford and - he had a limp and he - there was a little church in - in th'Adelphi called St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14765897\charrsid7603217 Anne\rquote s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217  as well as St John}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8212415\charrsid7603217 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
s Cathedral and up to you being about into standard four you went to St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14765897\charrsid7603217 Anne\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14364513\charrsid7603217 
 so you wouldn't have to go all that way a little school. So I was going for this girl, I can remember it well, and - her father worked - I was only as I say about eleven or twelve, I went to call for her for her dinner, for her to come to
 school when - her father was sat reading the paper home to his dinner from the Copper or somewhere and eating his dinner and - all at once in walked Father Foy. So - his wife said, ooh, here's the priest. See. So he put the thing over his plate - the pap
e
r over his plate that he was eating, stood up of course when the priest come. So priest does no more, I stood there and watched him, he done no more and picked the - paper up, picked the chop up he was having, it's Friday and it was a meatless day and he 
gets hold of the chop and he nearly rammed it down, he said, here, finish it - yes. And we run out - we - we run out - his girl, his daughter and me we run off to school and ooh - I said, nearly - nearly choked your father with the - it was funny.
